• Website organization: 
	My project includes 3 pages imitating a travel agency, suggesting various travel locations in Vietnam.
	In the first page, I added a background image at the top of the page, while using position relative for the header “Explore what Vietnam has to offer in 2023”. By organising the background image and header this way, I find it easier to catch the user’s attention and create a hook for them to look at the rest of my project. This page includes a navigation button, opening other pages in another tab – which allows convenience for the user since they don’t have to go back and forth to look at my website. The rest of the page are some text paragraphs and images I embedded to explain why the travel destination is attractive and images are used to increase the aesthetics of the page. For content about Ha Long Bay, I added a youtube video so the user can better imagine what Ha Long Bay looks like, without being restricted to solely images I had on my website. For content about Sapa, I embedded the sounds of birds chirping – since it is such a peaceful village surrounded by nature. There is also an option to go back to the top of the page after the user has finished scrolling the page.
	In the second page, the screen displays a table of package deals the travel agency offers for their Black-Friday sale. Here I displayed a table with 5 columns and 6 rows to show how much discount the user will get based on the time they book the trip. In the bottom half of this page, I used Javascript to create a dynamic content where images from the first page will be displayed and changed frequently. By doing this, the user will be reminded of the amazing scenery and incentivised to book their trip.
	In the last page, there is a form that the user can fill out as the first step of their booking. After the user has filled out this form, the travel agency will reach out to the user to match them with a trip. There are several types of information the user fills out in this page, such as personal information, what type of flight and accommodation they prefer and information about their trip (depart from, going to, date and time of checkin…) Mostly all information here is validated using javascript – if information type/phone number is missing or mismatched, or if the check-out date is before the check-in date – a warning message will be displayed. There is also a button to submit data and clear the form. 
	In the last page, it is important to notice there are multiple types of data the user needs to enter (name, phone number, email, text, number, radio buttons, check boxes dates…).
•	The highlight (bragging) part: 
In this project, I am most proud of the javascript content displaying changing images on Page 2. Learning this technology took a lot of time and a lot of trials and errors for me to display it correctly. I had to use multiple learning websites (developer.mozilla and w3school) to understand how the switch statement works. I also consulted some youtube videos to see how the switch function is applied. 
I am also very proud of how I was able to validate check-out time is supposed to be later than check-in time. Not only did I validate missing check-in/check-out date, I was also able to display a warning message if the user inputs date orders incorrectly. This is particularly useful in reducing the hassle for the travel company – since they won’t have to discuss back and forth with the customer about their travel dates.
